commit 0d43ec9d946dca0470378bdca1384edf9741565d
Author: Edward Swernofsky <edabsw@gmail.com>
Date:   Sat Apr 11 21:43:57 2026 -0400

    fix(render/svdag): inside-leaf origins use exit-face normal (hash-thing-2nd)
    
    Pre-2nd the analytical face-normal derivation in both svdag.rs and
    svdag_raycast.wgsl assumed the ray origin was outside the occupied
    leaf. It computes per-axis slab entry times and picks the axis with
    max `tmin_v` as the last face crossed. When the origin is already
    inside a filled voxel, every `tmin_v` component is negative, so the
    argmax picks the least-negative axis — which maps to the nearest BACK
    face of the voxel. The normal points inward, Lambertian flips sign,
    and the voxel shades as if lit from behind.
    
    Reachable via the orbit camera on deep zoom (src/render/renderer.rs +
    src/main.rs) — no occupancy clamp before shading, so the eye can land
    inside a filled leaf in a dense scene.
    
    Fix (option 1 from the bead — exit-face fallback): detect inside-leaf
    via `all(tmin_v < 0)`, then pick the nearest EXIT face (argmin of
    `tmax_v`) with the normal pointing in the direction of travel (sign
    aligned with `rd` on the exit axis). Textbook "about to emerge from
    the voxel" convention, smallest self-contained fix, keeps the
    analytical normal invariant on the hot path.
    
    Mirrored 1:1 in CPU oracle + shader. Both cascades use `<=` on the
    exit-face picker so ties break identically on exact two-axis exits,
    matching the existing `>=` convention on the entry-face picker.
    
    Test: leaf_hit_normal_inside_origin_picks_exit_face — plants the ray
    origin at the exact center of a filled voxel (32,32,32) in a level-6
    scene and fires along each of the six axes, asserting the normal is
    `sign(rd)` (exit face).
    
    143 tests pass.

