## Code Review
- **Date:** 2026-04-12T00:17:33Z
- **Model:** Codex (GPT-5 family; exact session model ID unavailable in this session)
- **Branch:** onyx/rv4-svdag-surface-normals
- **Latest Commit:** 4374da6
- **Linear Story:** N/A (`hash-thing-rv4`)
---

**Scope / Validation**

- Read-only review against local `origin/main` via `git diff origin/main...HEAD`; the branch currently shows `ahead 1, behind 2` vs local `origin/main`. I did not run `git fetch` / `git pull` because this session was explicitly read-only and network-restricted.
- `cargo test`: 134 passed, 0 failed.
- `cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings`: 0 warnings, 0 errors.

**General Feedback**

This branch fixes the reported flat-looking SVDAG shading in the common case by replacing the old ray-direction shade with an analytical leaf-face normal in both the shader and the CPU oracle, and by aligning the SVDAG lighting/fog constants with `src/render/raycast.wgsl`. The added tests cover axis-aligned hits, corner tie-break non-degeneracy, and miss initialization well.

1. **Important** — ✅ Confirmed — `src/render/svdag_raycast.wgsl:221-250`, mirrored in `src/render/svdag.rs:482-511`
   The new normal derivation assumes the ray origin is outside the occupied leaf. It computes `tmin_v` from `ro_local` to the leaf AABB and uses the entry face as the shading normal. When the camera/ray origin is already inside a filled leaf, that logic selects the face behind the origin, so the normal points inward and the Lambertian term is flipped. This is reachable with the current orbit camera because zoom can place the eye inside the unit cube (`src/main.rs:297`, `src/render/renderer.rs:347`, `src/render/renderer.rs:520-523`), and there is no occupancy collision/clamp before shading. Because the CPU oracle mirrors the same math, the new tests still pass and will not catch this case. Handle inside-leaf rays separately by using the exit face (`tmax`) when the origin is already inside the leaf, or by advancing to the leaf boundary before computing the normal.

**Residual Risks**

- Once the inside-leaf case is fixed, add a regression that starts a ray inside a filled voxel and asserts the expected exit-face normal so the CPU/GPU mirror cannot drift on that path.

