### General Feedback
This is the right fix direction. The committed change updates both `octant_of` implementations to the same strict-`>` + `rd >= 0.0` midpoint rule and threads `rd` through both CPU call sites, which matches the failure mode described in the 6hd reproducer.

Validation was clean on the code I reviewed: `cargo test` passed with 140 passed, 0 failed. I did not run the template's `npm` commands because this repo is Rust, not Node. I also did not sync/rebase the branch because the request was explicitly read-only; at review time the branch was `ahead 1, behind 2` versus local `origin/main`, so this report is about commit `272ce42` itself rather than post-rebase integration.

I do not see a correctness blocker in the committed implementation. The main gap is validation discipline around the CPU/GPU parity claim.

1. **Important** — ✅ Confirmed — `src/render/svdag.rs:1722-1828`, `src/render/svdag_raycast.wgsl:95-100`
   The new regression tests only exercise `cpu_trace::octant_of`; they do not exercise the WGSL `octant_of` or add any CPU↔GPU parity guard for this rule. That matters here because the branch's load-bearing invariant is not merely "Rust helper returns the right bitmask," it is "CPU and shader stay byte-equivalent on midpoint ties." Right now, a future edit that drifts only `src/render/svdag_raycast.wgsl` can silently reintroduce the bug with all new 6hd tests still green. This should have a guard of the same caliber as `render::wgsl_drift_guard::wgsl_metadata_shift_matches_rust`: either a textual drift guard pinning the comparator/tiebreak expression, or a golden parity test that proves CPU and shader choose the same octant for the midpoint-tie cases, especially the `(1.0, -1e-6, 0.0)` reproducer.

2. **Potential** — ✅ Confirmed — `src/render/svdag.rs:1778-1789`
   The reproducer is pinned only at the helper boundary (`pos`, `rd`, `node_min`, `half`), not as a traversal-level regression with distinguishable sibling outcomes. I understand why: the author says the full integration path is numerically fragile to reproduce end-to-end. Still, this means the suite proves "the helper returns octant 1 for these inputs," not the stronger statement "after `step_past`, traversal now walks the correct sibling instead of the wrong one." If this bug family has already burned the project once, I would prefer one small scene-level regression where octants 1 and 3 have different contents and the recorded traversal proves the reproducer ray lands in octant 1.

### Assessment
Architecturally, the fix addresses the right root cause instead of papering over symptoms: the old midpoint rule was direction-blind, and the new one makes sibling choice depend on the ray sign exactly where the old logic was ambiguous.

Tactically, the code change itself is consistent across CPU and WGSL, and the new unit tests are useful. The weakness is that the tests stop one layer short of the actual invariant this branch needs to defend.

