+## Code Review
+- **Date:** 2026-04-12T01:57:57Z
+- **Model:** Codex (GPT-5 family; exact session model ID unavailable in this session)
+- **Branch:** onyx/2nd-inside-leaf-normal
+- **Latest Commit:** 0d43ec9d946dca0470378bdca1384edf9741565d
+- **Linear Story:** N/A (`hash-thing-2nd`)
+---
+
+### General Feedback
+This is the right fix direction. The new `all(tmin_v < 0)` detector correctly separates the strict-inside case from the existing entry-face path, and the CPU/WGSL implementations in `src/render/svdag.rs` and `src/render/svdag_raycast.wgsl` are structurally mirrored. For the explicit `rd_axis = 0 -> inf` concern, the strict-inside axis-aligned cases are fine: the zero-direction axes contribute `tmax = +inf`, so the exit-face `argmin(tmax_v)` still selects the moving axis, not a zero axis.
+
+Validation was branch-only. The active worktree has an unrelated uncommitted edit in `src/render/mod.rs`, so I re-ran checks from a clean `git archive HEAD` export of commit `0d43ec9`. In that clean tree, `cargo test` passed with 143 passed / 0 failed, `cargo test leaf_hit_normal_inside_origin_picks_exit_face` passed 1/1, and `cargo test render::wgsl_drift_guard` passed 2/2. I did not run the template's `npm` commands because this repo is Rust, and I did not `git fetch` / `pull` because the request was read-only and the session is network-restricted.
+
+No blocker on the committed runtime fix itself. The one branch-local issue is parity protection.
+
+1. **Important** — ✅ Confirmed — `src/render/svdag.rs:519-547`, `src/render/svdag_raycast.wgsl:248-281`, `src/render/mod.rs:34-63`
+   `hash-thing-6hd` set the correct precedent here: when a fix introduces a load-bearing CPU/WGSL comparator or tie-break invariant, add a `wgsl_drift_guard` pin so a shader-only edit cannot silently drift from the CPU oracle. This branch introduces exactly that kind of surface: the strict `inside = all(tmin_v < 0)` classifier, the `argmin(tmax_v)` exit-face picker, and the `<=` tie-breaks that keep CPU/WGSL parity on tied exits. But the committed tree still has only two drift-guard tests, `wgsl_metadata_shift_matches_rust` and `wgsl_svdag_octant_of_tiebreak_matches_rust`; there is no `hash-thing-2nd` companion in `src/render/mod.rs`. The new regression `leaf_hit_normal_inside_origin_picks_exit_face` exercises only the CPU oracle, so a future WGSL-only drift on this inside-leaf branch can reintroduce parity bugs with all `hash-thing-2nd` tests still green. This should be guarded the same way `hash-thing-6hd` is.
+
+2. **Potential** — ⬇️ Lower priority, valid but non-blocking — `src/render/svdag.rs:1717-1754`
+   The new regression covers only strict-interior, center-origin rays on the six cardinal axes. That proves each exit-axis branch exists, but it does not pin the exact boundary semantics of the new strict `inside = all(tmin_v < 0)` classifier for `ro` exactly on a leaf face, edge, or corner, nor an off-axis strict-interior ray where all selected `tmax` values are finite. I do not see a correctness bug in the committed math: the strict `< 0` choice appears intentional, and the existing outside-entry and corner-entry tests still pass. Still, given the stated risk surface for this bead, one face-start case and one diagonal inside-start case would make that contract executable instead of documentary.
+
+### Assessment
+The runtime fix itself looks mechanically correct, and the committed branch passes cleanly in a clean export. The missing `hash-thing-2nd` shader drift-guard is the one review issue worth carrying forward, because it is the exact class of protection the project already learned to add in `hash-thing-6hd`.

